This is a solo project looking at a single dataset containing data on Steam games and attempting to predict certain data about a given game given other data. My primary features are Categorical data about a game including its Category, Genre, and Tags as well as Numerical data regarding the game's price.

The dataset has so many features, they can't all fit into the displayed table! There are also so many data points that they also couldn't easily fit in a display. Let's look at a few individual pieces of the data and see what we can do with them.

Price Ranges

A Numerical piece of data is a game's price. Let's start there and see how frequently certain prices come up in our dataset.

In[47]:

There appear to be a few 'ceilings' in pricing. Three games in particular ascend to 1,000 while many games hit the $200 mark precisely. Let's look at the instances of pricing.

In[48]:
price_counts = df["Price"].value_counts()# Get the number of instances of each price

plt.xlabel("Game Pricee")
plt.ylabel("Occurrences")
Out[48]:

The above graph is unrecognizably disoriented on the x axis. Most of our data has unique prices, which isn't good. Let's trim our data to only instances of prices with at least 10 games associated. Also, we'll sort our x axis so that we can see how our prices are distributed.

In[49]:
price_counts = df["Price"].value_counts()# Get the number of instances of each price
price_counts = price_counts[price_counts>10]
price_counts = pd.DataFrame(sorted(price_counts.items()), columns=["Price", "count"])
price_counts.plot(x='Price', y='count', kind='bar', legend=False, figsize=(20,3))# Plot the graph (expanded)
plt.title("Occurrences of Each Price")
plt.xlabel("Game Price")
plt.ylabel("Occurrences")
Out[49]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'Occurrences')

Now we have a decent-looking graph with several 'spikes' representing popular game prices. Free games are most popular with prices at 0.99 and 5.99 also being popular. Now that we know there 'break points,' let's re-integrate the data we cut out y breaking our data into ranges of prices rather than every single price value.

In[50]:

Before we can do anything with our labels, we need to properly clean and separate this data. Games can be a part of multiple Categories, but currently each unique combination of Categories is its own unique label. The same is true for Genres and Tags. Before we do anything, we need to separate out each label and make sure that two games that share a label are represented as such. Below is an example of a game with multiple tags.

In[54]:

To recap: We now have a game's:

  • Price Range
  • Categories
  • Genres
  • Tags

Using some of these, perhaps we can predict a fourth. Let's start with using our Categories and Genres to predict if a game has a certain Tag.

We'll build a KNN Model later to find games that have similar Categories and Genres and see if we can predict if a game has a particular tag.

from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsRegressor
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error

trainData, testData, trainLabel, testLabel = train_test_split(genres, df["Price"], test_size=0.25)
In[71]:
k_list = list(range(1, 50))# Get numbers 1 - 5
mse_list_train = []
mse_list_test = []

# For each k, get the MAE for each k value and append it to the appropriate list.
for k in k_list:
  # Train Model at given k
  model = KNeighborsRegressor(n_neighbors=k)
  model.fit(trainData,trainLabel)

  # Get training data prediction
  predLabels = model.predict(trainData)
  mse = mean_squared_error(np.array(trainLabel), predLabels)
  mse_list_train.append(mse)

  # Get test data prediction
  predLabels = model.predict(testData)
  mse = mean_squared_error(np.array(testLabel), predLabels)
  mse_list_test.append(mse)
In[72]:

plt.xlabel("K")
plt.ylabel("MSE")
plt.title("KNNModel MSE at Predicting Price given Genre")
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Release Month

Future Plans

To recap everything we have:

  • We've broken our games into a set of 15 price ranges
  • We can access an enormous number of categories, genres, and tags
  • We've started a model that uses categories and genres to predict if a game has a particular tag
  • We've added a 'Month' category from our 'Release Date'

I'd like to use our current features, the above, and build correlation matrices between them and discover which features may be 'noisy.' Currently, we have too much data for our model which prevents us from running it quickly or with larger K values.

Ideally, I would like to select several Tags that have a high correlation to several other factors and attempt to predict each of those tags given my input data. I believe that adding the 'Required age' feature will help to predict tags like 'Sexual content' or 'Violence'; so I may well add that feature next before improving my model.

  • Add additional images for clarity and quality in deliverable.
